"Botto-Mahan C., Campos R., Acuña-Retamar M., Coronado X., Cattan P.E., Solari A.","Temporal variation of trypanosoma cruzi infection in native mammals in chile",2010,"Vector-Borne and Zoonotic Diseases","10","3",,"317","319",,,10.1089/vbz.2009.0006,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77951964229&partnerID=40&md5=5696eb115285c06a9e0473fb6077bd9d","Departamento de Ciencias Ecológicas, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Chile, Casilla 653, Santiago, 1111, Chile; Programa de Biología Celular y Molecular, Instituto de Ciencias Biomédicas, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Departamento de Ciencias Biológicas, Facultad de Ciencias Veterinarias, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Department of Pathology, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM, United States","Botto-Mahan, C., Departamento de Ciencias Ecológicas, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Chile, Casilla 653, Santiago, 1111, Chile; Campos, R., Programa de Biología Celular y Molecular, Instituto de Ciencias Biomédicas, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Acuña-Retamar, M., Departamento de Ciencias Biológicas, Facultad de Ciencias Veterinarias, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile, Department of Pathology, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM, United States; Coronado, X., Programa de Biología Celular y Molecular, Instituto de Ciencias Biomédicas, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Cattan, P.E., Departamento de Ciencias Biológicas, Facultad de Ciencias Veterinarias, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Solari, A., Programa de Biología Celular y Molecular, Instituto de Ciencias Biomédicas, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile","In the present study, we compared Trypanosoma cruzi infection in four native mammals from a hyperendemic area of Chagas disease in Chile for two different periods to assess the occurrence of interannual variation (1999-2000 vs. 2005-2006). Parasite detection in mammals is performed by polymerase chain reaction assays and confirmed by Southern blot analysis and hybridization test with a universal probe. Results showed significant differences in the levels of T. cruzi infection between the compared periods. We suggest that the major El Niño event occurred in 1997-1998, a large-scale global climatic fluctuation, could be indirectly explaining the extremely high T. cruzi infection in 1999-2000 by means of a time-lag response of the wild transmission cycle of Chagas disease in semiarid Chile after the irruption of small rodent populations. © 2010, Mary Ann Liebert, Inc.","Chagas disease; ENSO; Trypanosoma cruzi; Wild reservoirs","article; Chagas disease; Chile; climate change; controlled study; endemic disease; epidemic; hybridization; nonhuman; polymerase chain reaction; priority journal; protist life cycle stage; semiarid climate; Southern blotting; Trypanosoma cruzi; Animals; Chagas Disease; Chile; Mammals; Opossums; Rodent Diseases; Rodentia; Time Factors; Trypanosoma cruzi; Mammalia; Rodentia; Trypanosoma cruzi",,,,,,"Botto-Mahan, C., Acuña-Retamar, M., Campos, R., Cattan, P.E., European rabbits (oryctolagus cuniculus) are naturally infected with different trypanosoma cruzi genotypes (2009) Am. J. Trop Med. Hyg., 80, pp. 944-946; Botto-Mahan, C., Ortiz, S., Rozas, M., Cattan, P., DNA evidence of trypanosoma cruzi in the chilean wild vector mepraia spinolai (hemiptera: Reduviidae) (2005) Mem. Inst. Oswaldo Cruz., 100, pp. 237-239; Jiménez, L., Lorca, M., Trypanosomiasis Americana en vertebra-dos silvestres y su relación con el vector triatoma spinolai (1990) Arch. Med. Vet., 22, pp. 179-183; Keesing, F., Holt, R.D., Ostfeld, R.S., Effects of species diversity on disease risk (2006) Ecol. Lett., 9, pp. 485-498; Kollien, A.H., Schaub, G.A., The development of trypanosoma cruzi in triatominae (2000) Parasitol Today, 16, pp. 381-387; Lima, M., Stenseth, N.C., Leirs, H., Jaksic, F.M., Population dynamics of small mammals in semiarid regions: A comparative study of within-year demographic variability in two rodent species (2003) Proc. R Soc. Lond B, 270, pp. 1997-2007; McMichael, A.J., Global climate change: Will it affect vector-borne infectious diseases? (2003) Int. Med. J., 33, pp. 554-555; Panzera, F., Dujardin, J.P., Nicolini, P., Caraccio, M.N., Genomic changes of chagas disease vector, south america (2004) Emerg. Infect. Dis., 10, pp. 438-446; Pascual, M., Rodo, X., Ellner, S.P., Colwell, R., Cholera dynamics and el niño-southern oscillation (2000) Science, 289, pp. 1766-1769; Rozas, M., Botto-Mahan, C., Coronado, X., Ortiz, S., Coexistence of trypanosoma cruzi genotypes in wild and period-omestic mammals in Chile (2007) Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg., 77, pp. 647-653; Telleria, J., Lafay, B., Virreira, M., Barnabe, C., Trypanosoma cruzi: Sequence analysis of the variable region of kinetoplast minicircles (2006) Exp. Parasitol., 114, pp. 279-288; Zell, R., Global climate change and the emergence/re-emergence of infectious diseases (2004) Int. J. Med. Microbiol, 293, pp. 16-26","Botto-Mahan, C.; Departamento de Ciencias Ecológicas, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Chile, Casilla 653, Santiago, 1111, Chile; email: cbotto@uchile.cl",,,,,,,,15303667,,VZDEB,19505255,"English","Vector Borne Zoonotic Dis.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-77951964229
